# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: threat-intelligence
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Sources of cyber threat intelligence include open-source data, social media, operational and technical intelligence, device log files, forensic analysis, internet traffic, as well as data from the dark web and deep web.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Modern CTI programs stand out from just using raw security data because they combine technical monitoring, outside intelligence sources, and analysis methods to prepare specific and useful assessments about cyber threats aimed at particular organizations or business sectors.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Analytical interpretation gives context to attackers’ actions, capabilities, and intentions, helping organizations set priorities and allocate security resources effectively.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] When companies base decisions on intelligence and analysis, they can act proactively instead of just reacting to security incidents, stopping breaches before they happen.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] This approach has become increasingly important in recent years, as IBM estimates that exploiting vulnerabilities is the most common way companies are breached, making up 47% of all attacks.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] The COVID-19 pandemic and the rise in remote work have also contributed to increased vulnerability to threats, making corporate data more exposed.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Due to growing threats on the one hand, and increasing analytical demands on the other, many companies have decided in recent years to outsource their threat analytics tasks to a managed security service provider (MSSP).
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Cyber threat analytics has also become an important component of modern Security Operations Centers (SOCs), where threat intelligence data is used to enrich alerts, identify malicious infrastructure, and support incident response and threat hunting activities.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] There are three categorical levels of cyber threat intelligence: tactical, operational, and strategic.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Each serves a distinct audience and purpose in building a comprehensive threat assessment.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Technical threat analysis focuses on machine-readable indicators of compromise (IoCs): malicious IP addresses, domain names, file hashes, and command-and-control (C2) servers or infrastructure.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] This enables automated detection and response.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] While the conventional distinction is between strategic, tactical, and operational analytics, some large organizations often define technical threat analytics as a separate (fourth) category essential for Security Operations Centers (SOCs).
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Some threat analytics platforms also distinguish between indicator-based analytics and behavior-based analytics.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Indicator-based analytics focuses on specific technical artifacts: malicious IP addresses, file hashes, etc.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Behavior-based analytics analyzes attackers’ tactics and techniques to detect threats that may change their infrastructure or indicators over time.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] To obtain effective analytical insights, it is necessary to combine data from internal security tools with external technical and strategic reports to gain a more comprehensive view of the threat landscape.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] The process of developing cyber threat intelligence is a circular and continuous process, known as the intelligence cycle, which is composed of five phases, carried out by intelligence teams to provide to leadership relevant and convenient intelligence to reduce danger and uncertainty.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] The five phases are: 1) planning and direction; 2) collection; 3) processing; 4) analysis; 5) dissemination.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] In planning and directing, the customer of the intelligence product requests intelligence on a specific topic or objective.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Then, once directed by the client, the second phase begins, collection, which involves accessing the raw information that will be required to produce the finished intelligence product.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Finally, the dissemination phase, in which the newly selected threat intelligence is sent to the various users for their use.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] The intelligence cycle model in the field of cyber threat analysis is based on traditional intelligence methods used by military and government intelligence agencies, where structured analysis is employed to transform raw data into the insights needed for decision-making.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Cybersecurity researchers also highlight other factors for good threat intelligence, such as accuracy, completeness, timeliness, compatibility, and relevance to the environment where it will be used.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Threat analytics helps improve threat detection mechanisms by identifying attackers’ methods and behavioral patterns that are not yet detected by automated security monitoring systems.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Organizations often deploy specialized software known as threat intelligence platforms (TIPs) to aggregate, analyze, and distribute threat intelligence data.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Threat intelligence platforms gather data from both internal and external sources, including security system telemetry, open-source intelligence feeds, malware repositories, vulnerability databases, and reports from security vendors.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] By aggregating and correlating indicators of compromise (IoCs) like malicious IP addresses, domain names, file hashes, and command-and-control infrastructure, these platforms help security professionals better understand threat contexts and identify the most significant threats.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] TI platforms are commonly integrated with other cybersecurity systems.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Integrations with tools such as security information and event management (SIEM) systems, endpoint detection and response (EDR) solutions, and incident response platforms enable automated alert enrichment and faster investigation of security incidents.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Threat intelligence platforms also support threat hunting and incident response by organizing indicators and intelligence reports within searchable repositories, allowing analysts to correlate events and identify patterns associated with specific campaigns or threat actors.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Some threat intelligence platforms use automated data pipelines and machine learning techniques to process large volumes of threat data and generate analytical insights for proactive cybersecurity strategies.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Modern programs for collecting and analyzing cyber threat intelligence rely on standardized formats that enable automated exchange between organizations and security tools, as well as the processing of analytical data.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] STIX (Structured Threat Information Expression) is a standardized language for representing analytical information about cyber threats in a machine-readable format, allowing analysts to describe attackers, campaigns, vulnerabilities, and indicators within a structured data model.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Trusted Automated Exchange of Intelligence Information (TAXII) is a protocol for supporting the automated exchange of threat intelligence data, typically used to transmit intelligence in STIX format.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] The Traffic Light Protocol (TLP) is widely used in the exchange of threat intelligence to determine how sensitive information is shared among members of trusted communities.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Analysts use structured analytical models to understand the behavior of attackers and implement defensive measures.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] The Cyber Kill Chain model, developed by Lockheed Martin, describes the stages of a cyberattack as a linear progression: reconnaissance, weaponization (preparation of attack tools), delivery, exploitation of vulnerabilities, installation, command and control, and actions on objectives.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] This framework helps defenders identify at which stage an attack can be disrupted.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] The Diamond Model of Intrusion Analysis examines the relationships between four core features of any intrusion event: the adversary, their capabilities (tools and techniques), the infrastructure they use (domains, IP addresses, email addresses), and the victim.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Using these relationships across multiple events, analysts can pivot between incidents, identify patterns, and attribute activity to specific threat actors or campaigns.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] The MITRE ATT&CK framework is a knowledge base of adversary tactics and techniques based on real-world observations.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] It organizes attacker behavior into 14 tactics (the "why" of an action - initial access, persistence, privilege escalation, defense evasion, etc.), and hundreds of techniques (the "how" - specific methods used to achieve each tactic).
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Unlike the linear Cyber Kill Chain, ATT&CK provides a detailed matrix of adversary behaviors that can occur in any order or simultaneously.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Security teams use ATT&CK to map threat intelligence to defensive controls, assess coverage gaps, conduct red team exercises, and build detections aligned with actual adversary tradecraft.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] It has become the de facto standard for describing and sharing operational threat intelligence.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] The increasing volume and velocity of cyber threat data have led organizations to automate significant parts of the threat intelligence lifecycle, including data collection, processing, correlation, and distribution.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Automated threat intelligence systems typically ingest data from multiple sources, and then process and correlate this information to identify patterns of malicious activity.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Machine-readable standards and transport protocols (STIX and TAXII) are an important component of automated CTI systems.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Integration between threat intelligence platforms and security operations center (SOC) systems enables automated prioritization of alerts and enrichment of security events using intelligence indicators.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] The drawback of automated analytics systems is that they can generate false positives or rely on low-quality indicators, which means analysts have to verify the results and provide a contextual interpretation.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] For this reason, many organizations adopt a hybrid model in which automated systems perform large-scale data processing while human analysts focus on interpretation, attribution, and strategic assessment of cyber threats.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Attribution is the process of identifying who conducted a cyber attack: the individual actors, organized groups, or nation-state sponsors behind an intrusion.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] In threat intelligence, attribution helps organizations understand adversary intent, prioritize defenses, anticipate future targeting, and inform strategic decisions.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] It also supports law enforcement investigations and policy responses.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] However, attribution is inherently difficult and often remains probabilistic rather than definitive.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Attackers routinely employ obfuscation techniques: using proxy infrastructure, VPNs, compromised intermediary systems, and stolen or leased tools.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Advanced threat actors deliberately plant false flags by mimicking the TTPs, language, or infrastructure patterns of other groups to misdirect attribution efforts.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] As a result, different threat intelligence vendors take varying approaches to attribution.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Some explicitly attribute threat groups to specific nation-states or sponsoring organizations based on their analysis and confidence thresholds.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Others intentionally avoid geopolitical attribution, instead documenting only observable, undisputable facts, such as language artifacts in malware, shared infrastructure, or technical capabilities, and tracking adversary clusters by neutral designators.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] Attribution assessments are typically expressed with varying levels of confidence (low, medium, high) rather than certainty, and erroneous conclusions can have diplomatic, legal, or strategic consequences.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] In 2015 U.S. government legislation in the form of the Cybersecurity Information Sharing Act encouraged the sharing of CTI indicators between government and private organizations.
[src:threat-intelligence/cyber-threat-intelligence] In 2016, the U.S. government agency National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) issued a publication (NIST SP 800–150) which further outlined the necessity for Cyber Threat Information Sharing as well as a framework for implementation.
[src:threat-intelligence/indicator-of-compromise] An **indicator of compromise** (**IoC**) in computer forensics is an artifact observed on a computer network or within an operating system that, with high confidence, indicates a computer intrusion.
[src:threat-intelligence/indicator-of-compromise] Common IoCs include virus signatures, suspicious IP addresses, MD5 hashes of malware files, and malicious URLs or domain names associated with botnet command-and-control servers.
[src:threat-intelligence/indicator-of-compromise] Once IoCs are identified through incident response or forensic analysis, they can be used for early detection of future attacks with intrusion detection systems and antivirus software.
[src:threat-intelligence/indicator-of-compromise] Known indicators are often exchanged within the cybersecurity industry, commonly using the Traffic Light Protocol (TLP) to indicate how information may be shared.
[src:threat-intelligence/indicator-of-compromise] Other frameworks and standards are also used to support secure information sharing.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] OSINT, broadly defined, involves gathering and analyzing publicly accessible information to produce actionable insights.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Department of Homeland Security defines OSINT as intelligence derived from publicly available information, collected and disseminated promptly to address specific intelligence needs.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] NATO describes OSINT as intelligence obtained from publicly available information and other unclassified data with limited public distribution or access.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] The European Union defines OSINT as the collecting and analyzing information from open sources to generate actionable intelligence, supporting areas like national security, law enforcement, and business intelligence.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] The United Nations has also recognized OSINT’s potential, noting its value in monitoring member states’ compliance with international regulations across various sectors, including public health and human rights.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] In the private sector, companies like IBM define OSINT as the process of gathering and analyzing publicly available information to assess threats, inform decisions, or answer specific questions.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Similarly, cybersecurity firms such as CrowdStrike describe OSINT as the act of collecting and analyzing publicly available data for intelligence purposes.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] OSINT practices have been documented as early as the mid-19th century in the United States and early 20th century in the United Kingdom.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] OSINT in the United States traces its origins to the 1941 creation of the Foreign Broadcast Monitoring Service (FBMS), an agency responsible for the monitoring of foreign broadcasts.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] An example of their work was the correlation of changes in the price of oranges in Paris with successful bombings of railway bridges during World War II.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] The Aspin-Brown Commission stated in 1996 that US access to open sources was "severely deficient" and that this should be a "top priority" for both funding and DCI attention.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] In July 2004, following the September 11 attacks, the 9/11 Commission recommended the creation of an open-source intelligence agency.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] In March 2005, the Iraq Intelligence Commission recommended the creation of an open-source directorate at the CIA.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Following these recommendations, in November 2005 the Director of National Intelligence announced the creation of the DNI Open Source Center.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] The Center was established to collect information available from "the Internet, databases, press, radio, television, video, geospatial data, photos and commercial imagery." In addition to collecting openly available information, it would train analysts to make better use of this information.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] The center absorbed the CIA's previously existing Foreign Broadcast Information Service (FBIS), originally established in 1941, with FBIS head Douglas Naquin named as director of the center.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Then, following the events of 9/11 the Intelligence Reform and Terrorism Prevention Act merged FBIS and other research elements into the Office of the Director of National Intelligence creating the Open Source Enterprise.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Furthermore, the private sector has invested in tools which aid in OSINT collection and analysis.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Specifically, In-Q-Tel, a Central Intelligence Agency supported venture capital firm in Arlington, VA assisted companies develop web-monitoring and predictive analysis tools.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] In December 2005, the Director of National Intelligence appointed Eliot A.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Jardines as the Assistant Deputy Director of National Intelligence for Open Source to serve as the Intelligence Community's senior intelligence officer for open source and to provide strategy, guidance and oversight for the National Open Source Enterprise.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Jardines has established the National Open Source Enterprise and authored intelligence community directive 301.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Jardines returned to the private sector and was succeeded by Dan Butler who is ADDNI/OS and previously Mr.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] OSINT is distinguished from research in that it applies the process of intelligence to create tailored knowledge supportive of a specific decision by a specific individual or group.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] A guide by Ryan Fedasiuk, an analyst at the Center for Security and Emerging Technology, lists six tools open-source analysts can use to stay safe and utilize operational security (OPSEC) when conducting online investigations.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] These include VPNs, cached webpages, digital archive services, URL and file scanners, browser sandbox applications, and antivirus software.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Numerous lists of aggregated OSINT content are available on the web.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] The OSINT Framework contains over 30 primary categories of tools and is maintained as an open source project on GitHub.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] A main hindrance to practical OSINT is the volume of information it has to deal with information explosion.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] The amount of data being distributed increases at a rate that it becomes difficult to evaluate sources in intelligence analysis.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] To a small degree the work has sometimes been done by amateur crowd-sourcing.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Private individuals illegally collecting data for a foreign military or intelligence agency is considered espionage in most countries.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Espionage that is not treason (e.g. betraying one's country of citizenship) has been a tool of statecraft since ancient times.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] The open and accessible nature of public sources makes OSINT particularly vulnerable to contamination.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Extremist groups regularly use OSINT to spread to misinformation and spread their ideology.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Governments and state actors have been documented intentionally disseminating disinformation through public channels to influence perceptions, confuse adversaries, or undermine trust in open-source findings.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] This can include planting false information in news outlets, social media, official statements, or even manipulated geospatial data to deceive OSINT practitioners who rely on such sources.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] The OSINT Foundation is a professional association for OSINT practitioners in the United States Intelligence Community.
[src:threat-intelligence/open-source-intelligence] Citizens and seeks to raise the prominence of the open-source intelligence discipline.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] The STIX fonts are available as fully hinted OpenType/CFF fonts.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] The project was initiated in 1995 and officially released its first stable version (STIX 1.0) in May 2010, after 15 years of development, with subsequent updates including STIX Two released in 2016.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] There is currently no TrueType version of the STIX fonts available, but the STIX Mission Statement includes the intention to create one in the future.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] However, there exists an unofficial conversion of STIX Fonts (from the beta version release) to TrueType, suitable for use with software without OpenType support.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] STIX fonts also include natural language glyphs for Latin, Greek and Cyrillic.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] The family is designed to be visually compatible with the Times New Roman family, a popular choice in book publishing.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] Among the glyphs in STIX, 32.9% have been contributed by the project members.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] The commercial TeX vendor and TeX font foundry MicroPress has been contracted to create the additional glyphs.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] The STIX project will also create a TeX implementation.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] Goals also include incorporating the characters into Unicode, and ensuring that browsers can use them.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] Members of the STIX Fonts project, known collectively as the STI Pub consortium, include the American Institute of Physics, the American Chemical Society, the American Mathematical Society, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, the American Physical Society, and Elsevier.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] A beta version of the fonts was released on October 31, 2007.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] This version does not include enough of the OpenType mathematical layout features present in Cambria Math, so it is not usable to the fullest extent in Microsoft Office 2007.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] The Latin glyph set included in the beta version does not yet cover all the characters required to typeset in Eastern European languages.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] "Final design changes" were declared "complete" at the project website on June 9, 2008.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] A release by end of May 2009 for the "initial production release" was announced, still without the support for OpenType layout features of Office 2007 or TeX.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] In September 2009, the fonts went to the final packaging stage.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] However, in October, missing glyphs were discovered, adding a delay.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] The fonts were scheduled to be released in April 2010, and released on May 28, 2010.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] The project has taken considerably longer than forecast.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] The website has been updated only intermittently, and thus has regularly been out-of-date, with forecast milestones often being overshot.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] This version facilitates equation editing in recent versions of Microsoft Word.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] Version 1.1.0 with LaTeX support was released on May 29, 2013.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] On December 1, 2016, the official project website announced the release of STIX version 2.0.0.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] This was created by Ross Mills and John Hudson of Tiro Typeworks.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] Unlike the previous version, which closely matches Nimbus Roman No.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] 9 L, it is an original design loosely inspired by a smaller 10 point size of Times New Roman, with a higher x-height.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] In April 2018, the Type 1 version of the STIX Two fonts for use in LaTeX was released.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] At the same time, the STIX project hosting platform has been migrated to GitHub (https://github.com/stipub/stixfonts/).
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] The STIX Fonts are included in OS X in versions from Lion (10.7) onwards.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] The JavaScript framework MathJax uses the STIX fonts for including mathematics in web pages.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] Installing the fonts on the local computer improves MathJax's typesetting speed.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] The Math Editor equation editor uses STIX fonts as its primary font.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] A precursor to the STIX project is the ESSTIX (Elsevier Science STIX) font, developed and later donated by Elsevier.
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] It is currently available from the World Wide Web Consortium as part of the Amaya (web browser).
[src:threat-intelligence/stix] However, the STIX fonts are not used in most of the peer-reviewed journals published by Elsevier.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] In cybersecurity and risk assessment, a **threat actor** (or *threat agents*, *attackers*, or *adversaries*) is a person, group, organisation, state, or other entity with the ability to cause, carry, transmit, support, or exploit a threat.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Threat actors are commonly analysed according to their motivations, resources, technical capability, access to systems, relationship to a target, and degree of connection to state authority.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] They may exploit vulnerabilities, conduct social engineering, steal or monetise data, disrupt operations, or support other actors who carry out such activity.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Because the term covers a wide range of actors, researchers and security organisations use taxonomies that distinguish between groups such as cybercriminals, state-linked actors, ideologically motivated actors, thrill seekers or trolls, insiders, and competitors.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Threat actor classifications are used in risk management, cyber threat intelligence, and incident response to connect observed behaviour with possible objectives and likely future activity.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] The categories are not always mutually exclusive: the same actor may combine criminal, ideological, commercial, or state-linked motivations, and different organisations may use different names for similar actors.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] In risk assessment, threat actor analysis is used to identify who or what may create, carry, transmit, support, or exploit a threat, and how that actor relates to the system being assessed.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Rausand and Haugen classify threat actors by their relationship to the system, distinguishing between internal and external actors, and by intent, distinguishing between intentional and unintentional actors.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Threat actor classification may also support incident investigation.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Rogers argued that actor categories could be inferred from observable case points, such as tools used, messages left, data targeted, forensic knowledge, and the degree of damage, allowing investigators to assess likely motivation and skill level.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Later work similarly linked actor classification to operational analysis.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Chng, Lu, Kumar and Yau proposed a framework connecting hacker types, motivations and typical strategies, arguing that observed behaviour before or during an attack can help analysts infer the likely type of actor involved.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] At the strategic level, actor analysis may consider an actor's resources, capabilities, degree of state involvement, motivations and objectives.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Its 2026 report argued that these actors vary in resources, technical sophistication and relationships with states, making it traditional distinctions between state, civilian combatant roles, and legitimate and illegitimate conduct harder to apply.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Early taxonomies classified hackers by activity, skill, motivation, or criminal profile.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Landreth proposed six categories based on activity: novice, student, tourist, crasher, and thief.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Hollinger classified computer misuse into pirates, browsers, and crackers, describing a progression from less-skilled activity to more technically serious offences.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Chantler used attributes including activity, skill, knowledge, motivation, and duration of involvement to distinguish between an elite group, neophytes, and "losers and lamers".
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Parker proposed seven profiles of cybercriminals: pranksters, hacksters, malicious hackers, personal problem solvers, career criminals, extreme advocates, and malcontents, addicts, and irrational or incompetent people.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] In 2000, Marc Rogers proposed a taxonomy of hackers with seven, non-mutually-exclusive categories: newbie/tool kit users, cyber-punks, internals, coders, old guard hackers, professional criminals, and cyber-terrorists.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Rausand and Haugen distinguish between internal and external threat actors, and between intentional and unintentional threat actors.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Internal actors have some relationship with, access to, or position inside the system or organisation, while external actors operate from outside it.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Intentional actors seek to create, exploit, or support a threat event, whereas unintentional actors may cause or enable a threat event through error, negligence, accident, or lack of awareness.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Rogers later revised his hacker taxonomy into Novices, Cyber-punks, Internals, Petty Thieves, Virus Writers, Old Guard hackers, Professional Criminals, Information Warriors, and, more tentatively, Political Activists.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] In the model, motivation is grouped into four broad domains: curiosity, notoriety, revenge, and financial gain.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] A 2022 review by Chng, Lu, Kumar and Yau examined 11 hacker typologies published over three decades and proposed a unified framework linking hacker types, motivations, and strategies.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] The framework identified 13 hacker types and seven motivations, and argued that observed strategies during an attack can help analysts infer the likely type of actor involved.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Taxonomies of threat actors by governments are much more likely to include state-level threat actors.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] NIST treats threat-source identification as part of the risk-assessment process, alongside identifying threat events, vulnerabilities, likelihood and impact.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] In the EU, European Union Agency for Cybersecurity publishes the annual *ENISA Threat Landscape*, which analyses cyber incidents and adversary behaviour affecting the European Union.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] The 2025 report analysed selected incidents from the previous year and grouped activity around cybercrime, state-aligned activity, foreign information manipulation and interference, and hacktivism.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] In ENISA's 2025 analysis, hacktivist activity dominated reporting, representing almost 80% of recorded incidents and consisting mainly of low-level distributed denial-of-service operations.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] ENISA also reported increasing convergence between hacktivism, cybercrime and state-nexus activity, including state-aligned use of hacktivist personas, hacktivist adoption of ransomware, and false-flag or impersonation activity.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Canada defines threat actors as states, groups, or individuals who aim to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability with malicious intent.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] A threat actor must be trying to gain access to information systems to access or alter data, devices, systems, or networks.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] The Japanese government's National Centre of Incident Readiness and Strategy (NISC) was established in 2015 to create a "free, fair and secure cyberspace" in Japan.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] The NICS created a cybersecurity strategy in 2018 that outlines nation-states and cybercrime to be some of the most key threats.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] It also indicates that terrorist usage of the cyberspace needs to be monitored and understood.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] The Security Council of the Russian Federation published the cyber security strategy doctrine in 2016.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] This strategy highlights the following threat actors as a risk to cyber security measures: nation-state actors, cyber criminals, and terrorists.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Threat actors use techniques like Social engineering (security), and Phishing, alongside technical exploits like Cross-site scripting, SQL injection, and denial-of-service attacks.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] In practice, actor categories may overlap (Edward Snowden for example), and the same activity may combine features associated with hacktivism, cybercrime and state-linked operations.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] The lines between hacktivism, cybercrime and state-nexus activity had continued to blur, with shared toolsets, overlapping methods, fake personas, hacktivist adoption of ransomware, and cybercriminal or state-linked actors masquerading as other groups.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] Threat actor analysis also has limits as a risk-management method.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] NIST notes that risk assessments depend on their purpose, scope, assumptions, constraints, information sources, risk model and analytic approach, and that assessments are tied to particular time frames and organisational contexts.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-actor] NIST also warns that simple threat-vulnerability pairing may be undesirable or problematic where there are many threats and vulnerabilities, and recommends using risk scenarios to address some of those limitations.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] In computer security, a **threat** is a potential negative action or event enabled by a vulnerability that results in an unwanted impact to a computer system or application.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] A threat can be either a negative "intentional" event like hacking or an "accidental" negative event or otherwise a circumstance, capability, action, or event (incident is often used as a blanket term).
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] A *threat actor* who is an individual or group that can perform the threat action, such as exploiting a vulnerability to actualise a negative impact.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] An *exploit* is a vulnerability that a threat actor used to cause an incident.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] A resource (both physical or logical) can have one or more vulnerabilities that can be exploited by a threat agent in a threat action.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] The result can potentially compromise the confidentiality, integrity or availability properties of resources (potentially different than the vulnerable one) of the organization and others involved parties (customers, suppliers).
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] The so-called CIA triad is the basis of information security.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] The attack can be *active* when it attempts to alter system resources or affect their operation: so it compromises Integrity or Availability.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] A "*passive attack*" attempts to learn or make use of information from the system but does not affect system resources: so it compromises Confidentiality.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] OWASP (see figure) depicts the same phenomenon in slightly different terms: a threat agent through an attack vector exploits a weakness (vulnerability) of the system and the related security controls causing a technical impact on an IT resource (asset) connected to a business impact.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Countermeasures are also called security controls; when applied to the transmission of information are named security services.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] The overall picture represents the risk factors of the risk scenario.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] The widespread of computer dependencies and the consequent raising of the consequence of a successful attack, led to a new term cyberwarfare.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Nowadays the many real attacks exploit Psychology at least as much as technology.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Phishing and Pretexting and other methods are called social engineering techniques.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] The Web 2.0 applications, specifically Social network services, can be a mean to get in touch with people in charge of system administration or even system security, inducing them to reveal sensitive information.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Note that a threat type can have multiple origins.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Recent trends in computer threats show an increase in ransomware attacks, supply chain attacks, and fileless malware.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Ransomware attacks involve the encryption of a victim's files and a demand for payment to restore access.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Supply chain attacks target the weakest links in a supply chain to gain access to high-value targets.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Fileless malware attacks use techniques that allow malware to run in memory, making it difficult to detect.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Microsoft previously rated the risk of security threats using five categories in a classification called DREAD: Risk assessment model.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] The spread over a network of threats can lead to dangerous situations.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] In military and civil fields, threat level has been defined: for example INFOCON is a threat level used by the US.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Leading antivirus software vendors publish global threat level on their websites.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] In cybersecurity and risk assessment, a threat actor (or *threat agents*, *attackers*, or *adversaries*) is a person, group, organisation, state, or other entity with the ability to cause, carry, transmit, support, or exploit a threat.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] A collection of threats in a particular domain or context, with information on identified vulnerable assets, threats, risks, threat actors and observed trends.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Threats should be managed by operating an ISMS, performing all the IT risk management activities foreseen by laws, standards and methodologies.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Very large organizations tend to adopt business continuity management plans in order to protect, maintain and recover business-critical processes and systems.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Some of these plans are implemented by computer security incident response team (CSIRT).
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Threat management must identify, evaluate, and categorize threats.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Many organizations perform only a subset of these methods, adopting countermeasures based on a non-systematic approach, resulting in *computer insecurity*.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Information security awareness is a significant market.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] There has been a lot of software developed to deal with IT threats, including both open-source software and proprietary software.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Threat management involves a wide variety of threats including physical threats like flood and fire.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] While ISMS risk assessment process does incorporate threat management for cyber threats such as remote buffer overflows the risk assessment process doesn't include processes such as threat intelligence management or response procedures.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] Cyber threat management (CTM) is emerging as the best practice for managing cyber threats beyond the basic risk assessment found in ISMS.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] It enables early identification of threats, data-driven situational awareness, accurate decision-making, and timely threat mitigating actions.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] The SANS Institute has conducted research and surveys on the effectiveness of threat hunting to track and disrupt cyber adversaries as early in their process as possible.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-computer-security] According to a survey performed in 2019, "61% [of the respondents] report at least an 11% measurable improvement in their overall security posture" and 23.6% of the respondents have experienced a 'significant improvement' in reducing the dwell time.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] The traditional approach to enterprise security involves security teams using a variety of processes and tools to conduct incident response, network defense, and threat analysis.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] Integration between these teams and sharing of threat data is often a manual process that relies on email, spreadsheets, or a portal ticketing system.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] This approach does not scale as the team and enterprise grows and the number of threats and events increases.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] With attack sources changing by the minute, hour, and day, scalability and efficiency is difficult.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] The tools used by large Security Operations Centers (SOCs), for example, produce hundreds of millions of events per day, from endpoint and network alerts to log events, making it difficult to filter down to a manageable number of suspicious events for triage.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] Threat intelligence platforms make it possible for organizations to gain an advantage over the adversary by detecting the presence of threat actors, blocking and tackling their attacks, or degrading their infrastructure.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] Using threat intelligence, businesses and government agencies can also identify the threat sources and data that are the most useful and relevant to their own environment, potentially reducing the costs associated with unnecessary commercial threat feeds.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] Tactical use cases for threat intelligence include security planning, monitoring and detection, incident response, threat discovery and threat assessment.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] A TIP also drives smarter practices back into SIEMs, intrusion detection, and other security tools because of the finely curated, relevant, and widely sourced threat intelligence that a TIP produces.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] An advantage held by TIPs, is the ability to share threat intelligence with other stakeholders and communities.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] Adversaries typically coordinate their efforts, across forums and platforms.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] A TIP provides a common habitat which makes it possible for security teams to share threat information among their own trusted circles, interface with security and intelligence experts, and receive guidance on implementing coordinated counter-measures.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] Full-featured TIPs enable security analysts to simultaneously coordinate these tactical and strategic activities with incident response, security operations, and risk management teams while aggregating data from trusted communities.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] Threat intelligence platforms are made up of several primary feature areas that allow organizations to implement an intelligence-driven security approach.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] Threat intelligence platforms can be deployed as a software or appliance (physical or virtual) on-premises or in dedicated or public clouds for enhanced community collaboration.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] In recent years deployment models have increasingly shifted towards SaaS based threat intelligence platforms.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] The threat intelligence market includes vendors offering varying capabilities across the TIP landscape.
[src:threat-intelligence/threat-intelligence-platform] Providers generally differentiate based on their data collection methods, source coverage, and primary use cases.
